00:11:36.180 --> 00:11:53.040
Yeah, subinterpreters, in a Python process, when you run Python, everything that happens, all the machinery that's running your Python code is running with a certain amount of global state.

00:11:55.180 --> 00:11:59.760
And historically, you can think of it as, you know, across the whole process.

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:01.460
You've got a bunch of global state.

00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:13.460
If you look at all the stuff like in the sys module, sys.modules or sys.whatever, all those things are shared across the whole runtime.

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:21.480
So if you have different threads, for instance, running, they all share that stuff, even though you're going to have different code running in each thread.

00:12:22.640 --> 00:12:29.780
So all of that runtime state is everything that Python needs in order to run.

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:39.140
But what's interesting is that the vast majority of it, you can think of as the actual interpreter.

00:12:40.320 --> 00:12:48.640
And so that state, if we treat it as isolated and we're very careful about it, then we can have multiple of them.

00:12:50.100 --> 00:13:06.440
That means that when your Python code runs, that it can run with a different set of this global state, different modules imported, different things going on, different threads that are unrelated and really don't affect each other at all.

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:19.040
And then with that in mind, you can take it one step farther and say, well, let's completely isolate those and like not even have them share a GIL.

00:13:19.580 --> 00:13:23.080
Right. And then at that point, that's where the magic kind of happens.

00:13:23.260 --> 00:13:36.760
