is good for sub-interpreters and vice versa.

01:09:50.380 --> 01:09:59.360
that no gil probably really wouldn't be possible without a lot of the work that we've done to make a per interpreter gil possible.

01:10:01.179 --> 01:10:03.700
So I think that's one of the neat things.

01:10:04.440 --> 01:10:07.780
The future is looking bright for Python multi-core.

01:10:08.820 --> 01:10:12.980
And I'm excited to see where people go with all these things that we're adding.

01:10:15.380 --> 01:10:19.560
Anthony, when's the sub-interpreters programming design patterns

01:10:19.820 --> 01:10:20.320
about coming out?

01:10:23.560 --> 01:10:28.840
Yeah, my thoughts are, well, there's a sub-interpreters

01:10:28.840 --> 01:10:33.460
I mentioned in my book actually when it was like Python 3.9, I think.

01:10:36.560 --> 01:10:39.520
Because it was possible then, but it's changed quite a lot since.

01:10:41.660 --> 01:10:45.360
I guess some thoughts to leave people with.

01:10:45.370 --> 01:10:49.680
I think if you're a maintainer of a Python package

01:10:50.860 --> 01:10:52.820
or a C extension module in a Python package,

01:10:54.480 --> 01:10:56.400
there's going to be a lot more exotic scenarios

01:10:56.820 --> 01:10:59.100
for you to test coming in the next year or so.

01:11:01.380 --> 01:11:06.100
And some of those uncover things that you might have done

01:11:06.210 --> 01:11:09.020
or just kind of relied on the GIL with global state

01:11:09.440 --> 01:11:12.980
where that's not really desirable anymore

01:11:13.100 --> 01:11:14.520
and you're going to get bugs down the line.

01:11:15.540 --> 01:11:18.180
So I think with any of that stuff as a package maintainer,

01:11:18.180 --> 01:11:20.260
you want to test as many scenarios as you can

01:11:20.560 --> 01:11:24.280
so that you can catch bugs and fix them before your users find them.

01:11:25.440 --> 01:11:26.840
So if you are a package maintainer,

01:11:26.980 --> 01:11:30.420
there's definitely some things that you can start to look at now to test

01:11:32.060 --> 01:11:37.560
that's available in 313 Alpha 2 is at least probably the one I've tried,

01:11:37.760 --> 01:11:38.100
to be honest.

01:11:39.940 --> 01:11:46.960
and if you're a developer not necessarily a maintainer then I think this is a good time to

01:11:47.180 --> 01:11:54.920
start reading up on like parallel programming and how you need to design parallel programs

01:11:55.920 --> 01:12:01.660
and that those kind of concepts are the same across all languages and you know Python would

01:12:01.660 --> 01:12:06.780
be no different we just have different mechanisms for starting parallel work and joining it back

01:12:06.680 --> 01:12:13.100
together um but if you're interested in this and you want to run more code in parallel and there's

01:12:13.200 --> 01:12:20.340
definitely some stuff to read and some stuff to learn about in terms of um you know signals pipes

01:12:20.640 --> 01:12:28.800
queues um sharing data how you have locks and where you should put them um how deadlocks can occur

01:12:29.740 --> 01:12:33.420
um things like that so all of that stuff is the same in python as anywhere else we just have

01:12:33.380 --> 01:12:35.160
different mechanisms for doing it.

01:12:35.980 --> 01:12:36.600
All right.

01:12:36.880 --> 01:12:39.440
Well, people have some research work.

01:12:39.840 --> 01:12:41.320
I guess a really, really quick final question,

01:12:41.640 --> 01:12:43.400
Eric, and we'll wrap this up.

01:12:44.480 --> 01:12:46.040
Following up on what Anthony said,

01:12:46.200 --> 01:12:46.980
like test your stuff,

01:12:47.200 --> 01:12:48.420
make sure it works in a sub-interpreter.

01:12:48.580 --> 01:12:49.720
If for some reason you're like,

01:12:49.740 --> 01:12:53.400
my code will not work in a sub-interpreter and I'm not ready yet,

01:12:53.540 --> 01:12:55.920
is there a way to determine that your code is being run in

01:12:55.920 --> 01:13:00.340
a sub-interpreter rather than regularly from your Python code?

01:13:00.800 --> 01:13:06.820
Yeah, if you have an extension module that supports sub interpreters,

01:13:07.680 --> 01:13:13.120
then you will have updated your module to use what's called multi-phase init.

01:13:16.000 --> 01:13:18.660
And that's something that shouldn't be too hard to look up.

01:13:18.660 --> 01:13:20.420
I think I talked about it in the PEP.

01:13:22.100 --> 01:13:23.700
If you implement multi-phase init,

01:13:24.520 --> 01:13:27.900
then you've already done most of the work to support a sub interpreter.

01:13:29.480 --> 01:13:34.600
The, if, if you haven't,

01:13:35.560 --> 01:13:39.060
then your module can't be imported in a sub-interpreter.

01:13:39.240 --> 01:13:41.480
It'll actually fail with an import error.

01:13:41.660 --> 01:13:47.300
If you try and import it in a sub-interpreter or at least a sub-interpreter that has its own GIL.

01:13:48.040 --> 01:13:51.780
There are ways to create sub-interpreters that still share GIL and that sort of thing.

01:13:54.200 --> 01:13:57.120
But you, you just won't be able to import it at all.

01:13:58.200 --> 01:14:03.200
So like the read line module can't be imported in sub interpreters.

01:14:04.040 --> 01:14:13.460
The issue that Anthony ran into is kind of a subtle side effect of the check that we're doing.

01:14:14.260 --> 01:14:21.160
So, but really it boils down to if you don't implement multi-phase init,

01:14:22.560 --> 01:14:25.260
then you won't be able to import the module.

01:14:25.720 --> 01:14:26.880
You'll just get an importer.

01:14:27.260 --> 01:14:29.200
So that's, I mean, it makes it kind of straightforward.

01:14:30.320 --> 01:14:34.920
Yeah. Sounds good. More opt-in than opt-out. Yep. Right on.

01:14:35.700 --> 01:14:36.020
All right, guys.

01:14:36.280 --> 01:14:41.800
Thank you both for coming back on the show and awesome work is looking close to

01:14:41.800 --> 01:14:46.840
the fetish line and exciting. Thanks Michael. Yep. See y'all.

01:14:47.600 --> 01:14:47.720
Yeah.

